-- Allianz, Deutsche Boerse, Fuchs Petrolub, Siemens: German Equity Preview
-- Sarah Jones
-- 2010-07-19T06:53:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-18/allianz-deutsche-boerse-fuchs-petrolub-siemens-german-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Germany. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 The benchmark  DAX Index  fell 1.8 percent to 6,040.27 on
July 16.  
 Allianz SE  (ALV GY): Europe’s biggest insurer may increase
its business in eastern Europe by making acquisitions,  Die Welt 
reported, citing an interview with regional head  Manuel Bauer .
The shares declined 1.7 percent to 84.80 euros.  
 Deutsche Bank AG  (DBK GY): The country’s largest bank named
 Henry Cai  of UBS AG chairman of corporate finance in Asia and
head of the corporate and investment bank in China as it tries
to win market share in the region. The stock fell 3.1 percent to
47.67 euros.  
 Deutsche Boerse AG  (DB1 GY): Europe’s largest exchange
wants to do more direct business with institutional investors
such as asset managers, pension funds and insurers, Chief
Executive Officer  Reto Francioni  told  Welt am Sonntag . The
shares lost 1.9 percent to 50.35 euros.  
 Deutsche Post AG  (DPW GY): The postal company’s rebates for
corporate clients are being examined by Germany’s Federal
Network Agency after complaints from competitors,
 WirtschaftsWoche  reported. The shares declined 1.5 percent to
12.69 euros.  
 Fuchs Petrolub AG  (FPE3 GY): The German maker of
lubricants’ 2010 dividend will at least match the previous
year’s payout of 1.70 euros ($2.20) a share, Chief Executive
Officer  Stefan Fuchs  told  Frankfurter Allgemeine Sonntagszeitung 
in an interview. The shares declined 2.2 percent to 75.67 euros.  
 Heidelberger Druckmaschinen AG  (HDD GR): The world’s
largest maker of printing presses said preliminary orders in the
first quarter rose 43 percent from a year earlier to 786 million
euros, helped by increasing demand in China. The stock fell 4.6
percent to 7.30 euros.  
 Siemens AG  (SIE GY): Motorola Inc. is near a deal to sell
its wireless-network equipment business to Nokia Siemens
Networks for more than $1.3 billion, according to one person
familiar with the sale.  Jennifer Erickson , a spokeswoman for
Motorola, declined to comment.  
 Separately, Chief Executive Officer  Peter Loescher  signed a
memorandum of collaboration with Kazakhstan’s state-run railway
company worth as much as 400 million euros as part of German
Chancellor  Angela Merkel ’s visit to the central Asian country.
 The shares declined 1.1 percent to 74.23 euros.  
 ThyssenKrupp AG  (TKA GY): CA Cheuvreux raised its
recommendation for the steelmaker to “outperform” from
“underperform,” saying it expects “a market re-rating of the
stock.” The stock lost 1.2 percent to 21.53 euros.  
